{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784606373420,"sessionID":"ses_07d2d6659ffe0JNz4C04306Spy","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_00_F6TEAPOXpg8fBkuO0Qbr7266","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0092-deep-review-session-shipped-work/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","limit":40},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0092-deep-review-session-shipped-work/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n3:   \"version\": \"1.4.3.0\",\n4:   \"resourceContractVersion\": 1,\n5:   \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/packetKind/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All six modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n6:   \"discriminator\": {\n7:     \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n8:     \"packetKind\": \"The axis discriminator: 'workflow' for the five design-judgment modes (interface/foundations/motion/audit/md-generator) that act on a design axis; 'transport' for a packet that bridges to an external tool's CLI/MCP surface rather than performing design judgment itself.\",\n9:     \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/), playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline), or od-cli-transport (drives the external Open Design app's od CLI and stdio MCP server).\"\n10:   },\n11:   \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n12:     \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n13:     \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. For sk-design the packet folder IS its packetSkillName — the prefixed name (e.g. folder 'design-interface' == packetSkillName 'design-interface') — so no mode has a folder/name mismatch and grandfatheredFolderMismatch is false throughout.\",\n14:     \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true only when a packet folder differs from its packetSkillName (a preserved legacy mismatch). All six sk-design modes use folder == packetSkillName (the prefixed name), so none has a mismatch — grandfatheredFolderMismatch is false for all six.\",\n15:     \"command\": \"The bound slash command for the mode, recorded even on metadata-routed modes (same field sk-doc's mode-registry.json carries); null when the mode has no dedicated command today. The five design-judgment modes each have a dedicated /interface:* command; the sixth mode, the design-mcp-open-design transport, carries command:null and is reached only by mandatory pairing with a design-judgment mode, never by its own command.\"\n16:   },\n17:   \"extensions\": {\n18:     \"transform-verbs\": {\n19:       \"description\": \"Declares the transform-verb routing extension: framing-split verb aliases (interface-frame 'make it' applies the move; audit-frame 'should it be' evaluates it), with excludedAliases and aliasOnly carve-outs. Activates the in-place top-level transformVerbRouting block without relocating it — the hub router vocabulary, command projection parity, and playbook scenarios all read it at that location.\",\n20:       \"declaredField\": \"transformVerbRouting\"\n21:     },\n22:     \"transport-axis\": {\n23:       \"description\": \"Declares the TRANSPORT axis. packetKind:'transport' entries bridge to an external tool's CLI/MCP surface (backendKind:'od-cli-transport', routingClass:'metadata', mutatesWorkspace:false since writes land in the external tool, not this repo). They never perform design judgment themselves — every entry on this axis has its own mandatory-pairing contract requiring sk-design's own workflow modes before any design-affecting operation.\",\n24:       \"transports\": [\"design-mcp-open-design\"]\n25:     }\n26:   },\n27:   \"transformVerbRouting\": {\n28:     \"note\": \"Transform verbs split by framing: audit asks whether the move should happen; interface applies the requested move. excludedAliases governs free-text transform-verb framing only (e.g. 'make it typeset'); command-metadata.json's taskProjections is a separate layer governing which mode owns the SAME verb under an explicit slash command (e.g. /interface:foundations typeset). The two intentionally name the same verbs for different resolution paths -- this is not a collision.\",\n29:     \"interfaceFrame\": \"make it\",\n30:     \"auditFrame\": \"should it be\",\n31:     \"interfaceAliases\": [\"bolder\", \"quieter\", \"distill\", \"clarify\", \"delight\"],\n32:     \"aliasOnly\": [\"clarify\"],\n33:     \"commandProjectionParity\": [\"bolder\", \"quieter\", \"distill\", \"delight\"],\n34:     \"excludedAliases\": {\n35:       \"foundations\": [\"typeset\", \"colorize\"],\n36:       \"audit\": [\"harden\", \"polish\"]\n37:     }\n38:   },\n39:   \"modes\": [\n40:     {\n\n(Showing lines 1-40 of 166. Use offset=41 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n  \"version\": \"1.4.3.0\",\n  \"resourceContractVersion\": 1,\n  \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/packetKind/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All six modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n  \"discriminator\": {\n    \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n    \"packetKind\": \"The axis discriminator: 'workflow' for the five design-judgment modes (interface/foundations/motion/audit/md-generator) that act on a design axis; 'transport' for a packet that bridges to an external tool's CLI/MCP surface rather than performing design judgment itself.\",\n    \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/), playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline), or od-cli-transport (drives the external Open Design app's od CLI and stdio MCP server).\"\n  },\n  \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n    \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n    \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. For sk-design the packet folder IS its packetSkillName — the prefixed name (e.g. folder 'design-interface' == packetSkillName 'design-interface') — so no mode has a folder/name mismatch and grandfatheredFolderMismatch is false throughout.\",\n    \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true only when a packet folder differs from its packetSkillName (a preserved legacy mismatch). All six sk-design modes use folder == packetSkillName (the prefixed name), so none has a mismatch — grandfatheredFolderMismatch is false for all six.\",\n    \"command\": \"The bound slash command for the mode, recorded even on metadata-routed modes (same field sk-doc's mode-registry.json carries); null when the mode has no dedicated command today. The five design-judgment modes each have a dedicated /interface:* command; the sixth mode, the design-mcp-open-design transport, carries command:null and is reached only by mandatory pairing with a design-judgment mode, never by its own command.\"\n  },\n  \"extensions\": {\n    \"transform-verbs\": {\n      \"description\": \"Declares the transform-verb routing extension: framing-split verb aliases (interface-frame 'make it' applies the move; audit-frame 'should it be' evaluates it), with excludedAliases and aliasOnly carve-outs. Activates the in-place top-level transformVerbRouting block without relocating it — the hub router vocabulary, command projection parity, and playbook scenarios all read it at that location.\",\n      \"declaredField\": \"transformVerbRouting\"","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.worktrees/0092-deep-review-session-shipped-work/.opencode/skills/sk-design/mode-registry.json","text":"{\n  \"skill\": \"sk-design\",\n  \"version\": \"1.4.3.0\",\n  \"resourceContractVersion\": 1,\n  \"description\": \"Declarative mode registry: the single source of truth for the discriminator (workflowMode/packetKind/backendKind) PLUS the advisorRouting projection for sk-design. The hub reads this file to resolve a mode; the advisor routes any design query to the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode. All six modes route by hub membership (routingClass 'metadata'), so there is no advisor map entry per mode and no merged-identity projection — the advisor does not read this file at runtime.\",\n  \"discriminator\": {\n    \"workflowMode\": \"Public hub/mode key. Stable identity used by the hub router and this registry. Carried by every mode.\",\n    \"packetKind\": \"The axis discriminator: 'workflow' for the five design-judgment modes (interface/foundations/motion/audit/md-generator) that act on a design axis; 'transport' for a packet that bridges to an external tool's CLI/MCP surface rather than performing design judgment itself.\",\n    \"backendKind\": \"Which backend runs the mode: reference-base (cites the shared design reference base under references/), playwright-extract (runs the embedded Playwright CSS-extraction pipeline), or od-cli-transport (drives the external Open Design app's od CLI and stdio MCP server).\"\n  },\n  \"advisorRoutingContract\": {\n    \"routingClass\": \"How the advisor finds the mode. For sk-design every mode is 'metadata' = resolved by hub membership; the advisor routes the single identity sk-design and the hub picks the mode, so no mode carries an advisor map entry or a merged-identity projection.\",\n    \"packetSkillName\": \"The packet's SKILL.md name. For sk-design the packet folder IS its packetSkillName — the prefixed name (e.g. folder 'design-interface' == packetSkillName 'design-interface') — so no mode has a folder/name mismatch and grandfatheredFolderMismatch is false throughout.\",\n    \"grandfatheredFolderMismatch\": \"true only when a packet folder differs from its packetSkillName (a preserved legacy mismatch). All six sk-design modes use folder == packetSkillName (the prefixed name), so none has a mismatch — grandfatheredFolderMismatch is false for all six.\",\n    \"command\": \"The bound slash command for the mode, recorded even on metadata-routed modes (same field sk-doc's mode-registry.json carries); null when the mode has no dedicated command today. The five design-judgment modes each have a dedicated /interface:* command; the sixth mode, the design-mcp-open-design transport, carries command:null and is reached only by mandatory pairing with a design-judgment mode, never by its own command.\"\n  },\n  \"extensions\": {\n    \"transform-verbs\": {\n      \"description\": \"Declares the transform-verb routing extension: framing-split verb aliases (interface-frame 'make it' applies the move; audit-frame 'should it be' evaluates it), with excludedAliases and aliasOnly carve-outs. Activates the in-place top-level transformVerbRouting block without relocating it — the hub router vocabulary, command projection parity, and playbook scenarios all read it at that location.\",\n      \"declaredField\": \"transformVerbRouting\"\n    },\n    \"transport-axis\": {\n      \"description\": \"Declares the TRANSPORT axis. packetKind:'transport' entries bridge to an external tool's CLI/MCP surface (backendKind:'od-cli-transport', routingClass:'metadata', mutatesWorkspace:false since writes land in the external tool, not this repo). They never perform design judgment themselves — every entry on this axis has its own mandatory-pairing contract requiring sk-design's own workflow modes before any design-affecting operation.\",\n      \"transports\": [\"design-mcp-open-design\"]\n    }\n  },\n  \"transformVerbRouting\": {\n    \"note\": \"Transform verbs split by framing: audit asks whether the move should happen; interface applies the requested move. excludedAliases governs free-text transform-verb framing only (e.g. 'make it typeset'); command-metadata.json's taskProjections is a separate layer governing which mode owns the SAME verb under an explicit slash command (e.g. /interface:foundations typeset). The two intentionally name the same verbs for different resolution paths -- this is not a collision.\",\n    \"interfaceFrame\": \"make it\",\n    \"auditFrame\": \"should it be\",\n    \"interfaceAliases\": [\"bolder\", \"quieter\", \"distill\", \"clarify\", \"delight\"],\n    \"aliasOnly\": [\"clarify\"],\n    \"commandProjectionParity\": [\"bolder\", \"quieter\", \"distill\", \"delight\"],\n    \"excludedAliases\": {\n      \"foundations\": [\"typeset\", \"colorize\"],\n      \"audit\": [\"harden\", \"polish\"]\n    }\n  },\n  \"modes\": [\n    {","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":40,"totalLines":166,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/skills/sk-design/